010/**
011 * Contains code for manipulating colors as {@code int} and packed {@code float} values in the Oklab color space.
012 * Oklab is a very new color space that builds on the same foundation as IPT, but seems to be better-calibrated for
013 * uniform lightness and colorfulness, instead of just the emphasis on uniform hue that IPT has. Relative to IPT, Oklab
014 * has a noticeably smaller range in chromatic channels (IPT's protan and tritan can range past 0.8 or as low as 0.35,
015 * but the similar A and B channels in Oklab don't stray past about 0.65 at the upper end, if that), but it does this so
016 * the difference between two Oklab colors is just the Euclidean distance between their components. A slight difference
017 * between Oklab and IPT here is that IPT shrinks the chromatic channels to store their -1 to 1 range in a color float's
018 * 0 to 1 range, then offsets the shrunken range from -0.5 to 0.5, to 0 to 1; Oklab does not need to shrink the range,
019 * and only offsets it in the same way (both just add 0.5).
020 * <br>
021 * Here's <a href="https://bottosson.github.io/posts/oklab/">Bj√∂rn Ottosson's original post introducing Oklab</a>.
022 * So far, <a href="https://raphlinus.github.io/color/2021/01/18/oklab-critique.html">it stood up to analysis by Raph
023 * Levien</a>, and seems to be gaining fans quickly.
024 */
025public class ColorTools {
026        /**
027         * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 4 float components, here, L (luminance or lightness), A
028         * (a chromatic component ranging from greenish to reddish, called protan in IPT), B (a chromatic component ranging
029         * from bluish to yellowish, called tritan in IPT), and alpha (or opacity). L should be
030         * between 0 and 1, inclusive, with 0 used for very dark colors (almost only black), and 1 used for very light
031         * colors (almost only white). A and B range from 0.0 to 1.0, with grayscale results when both are about 0.5.
032         * There's some aesthetic value in changing just one chroma value. When A is high and B is low, the color is more
033         * purple/magenta, when both are low it is more bluish, when B is high and A is low, the color tends to be greenish,
034         * and when both are high it tends to be orange. When A and B are both near 0.5f, the color is closer to gray.
035         * Alpha is the multiplicative opacity of the color, and acts like RGBA's alpha.
036         * <br>
037         * This method bit-masks the resulting color's byte values, so any values can technically be given to this as
038         * L, A, and B, but they will only be reversible from the returned float color to the original L,
039         * A, and B values if the original values were in the range that {@link #channelL(float)}, {@link #channelA(float)},
040         * and {@link #channelB(float)} return. You can use {@link #inGamut(float, float, float)} to check if a given set of
041         * L, A, and B values is in-gamut, that is, it can be converted to and from an RGB color without going out of the
042         * valid range. If you just want to enforce that a color is in-gamut, you can use
043         * {@link #limitToGamut(float, float, float, float)}, which takes the same parameters this method does, or
044         * {@link #limitToGamut(float)} if you already have a packed float color that could be out-of-gamut.
045         *
046         * @param l     0f to 1f, lightness or L component of Oklab, with 0.5f meaning "no change" and 1f brightening
047         * @param a     0f to 1f, protan or A component of Oklab, with 1f more orange, red, or magenta
048         * @param b     0f to 1f, tritan or B component of Oklab, with 1f more green, yellow, or red
049         * @param alpha 0f to 1f, 0f makes the color transparent and 1f makes it opaque
050         * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
051         */
052        public static float oklab(float l, float a, float b, float alpha) {
053                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(((int) (alpha * 255) << 24 & 0xFE000000) | ((int) (b * 255) << 16 & 0xFF0000)
054                                | ((int) (a * 255) << 8 & 0xFF00) | ((int) (l * 255) & 0xFF));
055        }

057        /**
058         * An approximation of the cube-root function for float inputs and outputs.
059         * This can be about twice as fast as {@link Math#cbrt(double)}. This
060         * version does not tolerate negative inputs, because in the narrow use
061         * case it has in this class, it never is given negative inputs.
062         * <br>
063         * Has very low relative error (less than 1E-9) when inputs are uniformly
064         * distributed between 0 and 512, and absolute mean error of less than
065         * 1E-6 in the same scenario. Uses a bit-twiddling method similar to one
066         * presented in Hacker's Delight and also used in early 3D graphics (see
067         * https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fast_inverse_square_root for more, but
068         * this code approximates cbrt(x) and not 1/sqrt(x)). This specific code
069         * was originally by Marc B. Reynolds, posted in his "Stand-alone-junk"
070         * repo: https://github.com/Marc-B-Reynolds/Stand-alone-junk/blob/master/src/Posts/ballcube.c#L182-L197 .
071         * It's worth noting that while hardware instructions for finding the
072         * square root of a float have gotten extremely fast, the same is not
073         * true for the cube root (which has to allow negative inputs), so while
074         * the bit-twiddling inverse square root is no longer a beneficial
075         * optimization on current hardware, this does seem to help.
076         * <br>
077         * This is used when converting from RGB to Oklab, as an intermediate step.
078         * @param x any non-negative finite float to find the cube root of
079         * @return the cube root of x, approximated
080         */
081        private static float cbrtPositive(float x) {
082                int ix = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(x);
083                final float x0 = x;
084                ix = (ix>>>2) + (ix>>>4);
085                ix += (ix>>>4);
086                ix += (ix>>>8) + 0x2A5137A0;
087                x  = BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(ix);
088                x  = 0.33333334f*(2f * x + x0/(x*x));
089                x  = 0.33333334f*(2f * x + x0/(x*x));
090                return x;
091        }

093        /**
094         * Used when converting from Oklab to RGB, as an intermediate step.
095         * Really just {@code x * x * x}.
096         * @param x one of the LMS Prime channels to be converted to LMS
097         * @return an LMS channel value, which can be converted to RGB
098         */
099        private static float cube(final float x) {
100                return x * x * x;
101        }

103        /**
104         * Used when given non-linear sRGB inputs to make them linear, approximating with gamma 2.0.
105         * Really just {@code component * component}.
106         * @param component any non-linear channel of a color, to be made linear
107         * @return a linear version of component
108         */
109        private static float forwardGamma(final float component) {
110                return component * component;
111        }
112
113        /**
114         * Used to return from a linear, gamma-corrected input to an sRGB, non-linear output, using gamma 2.0.
115         * Really just gets the square root of component, as a float.
116         * @param component a linear channel of a color, to be made non-linear
117         * @return a non-linear version of component
118         */
119        private static float reverseGamma(final float component) {
120                return (float)Math.sqrt(component);
121        }

123        /**
124         * Converts a packed float color in the format produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)} to an RGBA8888 int.
125         * This format of int can be used with Pixmap and in some other places in libGDX.
126         * @param packed a packed float color, as produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)}
127         * @return an RGBA8888 int color
128         */
129        public static int toRGBA8888(final float packed)
130        {
131                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
132                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
133                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
134                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
135                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
136                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
137                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
138                final int r = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
139                final int g = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
140                final int b = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
141                return r << 24 | g << 16 | b << 8 | (decoded & 0xfe000000) >>> 24 | decoded >>> 31;
142        }

144        /**
145         * Converts a packed float color in the format produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)}
146         * to a packed float in RGBA format.
147         * This format of float can be used with the standard SpriteBatch and in some other places in libGDX.
148         * @param packed a packed float color, as produced by {@link ColorTools#oklab(float, float, float, float)}
149         * @return a packed float color as RGBA
150         */
151        public static float toRGBA(final float packed)
152        {
153                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
154                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
155                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
156                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
157                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
158                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
159                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
160                final int r = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
161                final int g = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
162                final int b = (int)(reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f)) * 255.999f);
163                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(r | g << 8 | b << 16 | (decoded & 0xfe000000));
164        }

166        /**
167         * Takes a color encoded as an RGBA8888 int and converts to a packed float in the Oklab format this uses.
168         * @param rgba an int with the channels (in order) red, green, blue, alpha; should have 8 bits per channel
169         * @return a packed float as Oklab, which this class can use
170         */
171        public static float fromRGBA8888(final int rgba) {
172                final float r = forwardGamma((rgba >>> 24) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
173                final float g = forwardGamma((rgba >>> 16 & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
174                final float b = forwardGamma((rgba >>> 8 & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
175
176                final float l = cbrtPositive(0.4121656120f * r + 0.5362752080f * g + 0.0514575653f * b);
177                final float m = cbrtPositive(0.2118591070f * r + 0.6807189584f * g + 0.1074065790f * b);
178                final float s = cbrtPositive(0.0883097947f * r + 0.2818474174f * g + 0.6302613616f * b);
179
180                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(
181                                      Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.2104542553f * l + 0.7936177850f * m - 0.0040720468f * s) * 255.999f         ), 0), 255)
182                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((1.9779984951f * l - 2.4285922050f * m + 0.4505937099f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 8
183                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.0259040371f * l + 0.7827717662f * m - 0.8086757660f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 16
184                                                | (rgba & 0xFE) << 24);
185        }

187        /**
188         * Takes a color encoded as an RGBA8888 packed float and converts to a packed float in the Oklab format this uses.
189         * @param packed a packed float in RGBA8888 format, with A in the MSB and R in the LSB
190         * @return a packed float as Oklab, which this class can use
191         */
192        public static float fromRGBA(final float packed) {
193                final int abgr = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
194                final float r = forwardGamma((abgr & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
195                final float g = forwardGamma((abgr >>> 8 & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
196                final float b = forwardGamma((abgr >>> 16 & 0xFF) * 0x1.010101010101p-8f);
197                final float l = cbrtPositive(0.4121656120f * r + 0.5362752080f * g + 0.0514575653f * b);
198                final float m = cbrtPositive(0.2118591070f * r + 0.6807189584f * g + 0.1074065790f * b);
199                final float s = cbrtPositive(0.0883097947f * r + 0.2818474174f * g + 0.6302613616f * b);
200                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(
201                                      Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.2104542553f * l + 0.7936177850f * m - 0.0040720468f * s) * 255.999f         ), 0), 255)
202                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((1.9779984951f * l - 2.4285922050f * m + 0.4505937099f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 8
203                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.0259040371f * l + 0.7827717662f * m - 0.8086757660f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 16
204                                                | (abgr & 0xFE000000));
205        }

217        /**
218         * Takes RGBA components from 0.0 to 1.0 each and converts to a packed float in the Oklab format this uses.
219         * @param r red, from 0.0 to 1.0 (both inclusive)
220         * @param g green, from 0.0 to 1.0 (both inclusive)
221         * @param b blue, from 0.0 to 1.0 (both inclusive)
222         * @param a alpha, from 0.0 to 1.0 (both inclusive)
223         * @return a packed float as Oklab, which this class can use
224         */
225        public static float fromRGBA(float r, float g, float b, final float a) {
226                r = forwardGamma(r);
227                g = forwardGamma(g);
228                b = forwardGamma(b);
229                final float l = cbrtPositive(0.4121656120f * r + 0.5362752080f * g + 0.0514575653f * b);
230                final float m = cbrtPositive(0.2118591070f * r + 0.6807189584f * g + 0.1074065790f * b);
231                final float s = cbrtPositive(0.0883097947f * r + 0.2818474174f * g + 0.6302613616f * b);
232                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(
233                                          Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.2104542553f * l + 0.7936177850f * m - 0.0040720468f * s) * 255.999f         ), 0), 255)
234                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((1.9779984951f * l - 2.4285922050f * m + 0.4505937099f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 8
235                                                | Math.min(Math.max((int)((0.0259040371f * l + 0.7827717662f * m - 0.8086757660f * s) * 127.999f + 127.5f), 0), 255) << 16
236                                                | ((int)(a * 255f) << 24 & 0xFE000000));
237        }

362        /**
363         * Gets the "chroma" or "colorfulness" of a given Oklab color. Chroma is similar to saturation in that grayscale
364         * values have 0 saturation and 0 chroma, while brighter colors have high saturation and chroma. The difference is
365         * that colors that are perceptually more-colorful have higher chroma that colors that are perceptually
366         * less-colorful, regardless of hue, whereas saturation changes its range depending on how colorful a value can be
367         * at its hue. That is, the most saturated color always has a saturation of 1, but if that color isn't perceptually
368         * very colorful, it could have a chroma that is somewhat lower than 1. I don't yet know the range of this function,
369         * other than it can't be negative, grayscale values have 0 chroma, and the most colorful values should be near 1,
370         * maybe as high as the square root of 2.
371         * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}
372         * @return a non-negative float that represents how colorful the given value is
373         */
374        public static float chroma(final float encoded) {
375                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(encoded);
376                final float a = ((decoded >>> 7 & 0x1FE) - 255) / 255f;
377                final float b = ((decoded >>> 15 & 0x1FE) - 255) / 255f;
378                return (float) Math.sqrt(a * a + b * b);
379        }

381        /**
382         * Gets a color as an Oklab packed float given floats representing hue, saturation, lightness, and opacity.
383         * All parameters should normally be between 0 and 1 inclusive, though any hue is tolerated (precision loss may
384         * affect the color if the hue is too large). A hue of 0 is red, progressively higher hue values go to orange,
385         * yellow, green, blue, and purple before wrapping around to red as it approaches 1. A saturation of 0 is grayscale,
386         * a saturation of 1 is brightly colored, and values close to 1 will usually appear more distinct than values close
387         * to 0, especially if the hue is different. A lightness of 0.001f or less is always black (also using a shortcut if
388         * this is the case, respecting opacity), while a lightness of 1f is white. Very bright colors are mostly in a band
389         * of high-saturation where lightness is 0.5f.
390         *
391         * @param hue        0f to 1f, color wheel position
392         * @param saturation 0f to 1f, 0f is grayscale and 1f is brightly colored
393         * @param lightness  0f to 1f, 0f is black and 1f is white
394         * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
395         * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
396         */
397        public static float floatGetHSL(float hue, float saturation, float lightness, float opacity) {
398                if (lightness <= 0.001f) {
399                        return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat((((int) (opacity * 255f) << 24) & 0xFE000000) | 0x7F7F00);
400                } else {
401                        return fromRGBA(FloatColors.hsl2rgb(hue, saturation, lightness, opacity));
402                }
403        }

405        /**
406         * Gets the saturation of the given encoded color as HSL would calculate it, as a float ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f,
407         * inclusive. This is different from {@link #chroma(float)}; see that method's documentation for details.
408         * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}
409         * @return the saturation of the color from 0.0 (a grayscale color; inclusive) to 1.0 (a bright color, inclusive)
410         */
411        public static float saturation(final float encoded) {
412                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(encoded);
413                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
414                if(Math.abs(L - 0.5) > 0.495f) return 0f;
415                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
416                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
417                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
418                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
419                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
420                final float r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
421                final float g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
422                final float b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
423                float x, y, w;
424                if(g < b) {
425                        x = b;
426                        y = g;
427                }
428                else {
429                        x = g;
430                        y = b;
431                }
432                if(r < x) {
433                        w = r;
434                }
435                else {
436                        w = x;
437                        x = r;
438                }
439                return x - Math.min(w, y);
440        }

442        /**
443         * Defined as per HSL; normally you only need {@link #channelL(float)} to get accurate lightness for Oklab.
444         * This ranges from 0.0f (black) to 1.0f (white).
445         * @param encoded a packed float Oklab color
446         * @return the lightness of the given color as HSL would calculate it
447         */
448        public static float lightness(final float encoded) {
449                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(encoded);
450                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
451                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
452                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
453                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
454                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
455                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
456                final float r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
457                final float g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
458                final float b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
459                float x, y, w;
460                if(g < b) {
461                        x = b;
462                        y = g;
463                }
464                else {
465                        x = g;
466                        y = b;
467                }
468                if(r < x) {
469                        w = r;
470                }
471                else {
472                        w = x;
473                        x = r;
474                }
475                float d = x - Math.min(w, y);
476                return x * (1f - 0.5f * d / (x + 1e-10f));
477        }

479        /**
480         * Gets the hue of the given encoded color, as a float from 0f (inclusive, red and approaching orange if increased)
481         * to 1f (exclusive, red and approaching purple if decreased).
482         * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}
483         * @return The hue of the color from 0.0 (red, inclusive) towards orange, then yellow, and
484         * eventually to purple before looping back to almost the same red (1.0, exclusive)
485         */
486        public static float hue(final float encoded) {
487                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(encoded);
488                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
489                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
490                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
491                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
492                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
493                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
494                final float r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
495                final float g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
496                final float b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
497                float x, y, z, w;
498                if(g < b) {
499                        x = b;
500                        y = g;
501                        z = -1f;
502                        w = 2f / 3f;
503                }
504                else {
505                        x = g;
506                        y = b;
507                        z = 0f;
508                        w = -1f / 3f;
509                }
510                if(r < x) {
511                        z = w;
512                        w = r;
513                }
514                else {
515                        w = x;
516                        x = r;
517                }
518                float d = x - Math.min(w, y);
519                return Math.abs(z + (w - y) / (6f * d + 1e-10f));
520        }

560        /**
561         * Gets a variation on the packed float color basis as another packed float that has its hue, saturation, value, and
562         * opacity adjusted by the specified amounts. Takes floats representing the amounts of change to apply to hue,
563         * saturation, value, and opacity; these can be between -1f and 1f. Returns a float that can be used as a packed or
564         * encoded color. The float is
565         * likely to be different than the result of {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)} unless hue, saturation,
566         * value, and opacity are all 0. This won't allocate any objects.
567         * <br>
568         * The parameters this takes all specify additive changes for a color component, clamping the final values so they
569         * can't go above 1 or below 0, with an exception for hue, which can rotate around if lower or higher hues would be
570         * used. As an example, if you give this 0.4f for saturation, and the current color has saturation 0.7f, then the
571         * resulting color will have 1f for saturation. If you gave this -0.1f for saturation and the current color again
572         * has saturation 0.7f, then resulting color will have 0.6f for saturation.
573         *
574         * @param basis      a packed float color that will be used as the starting point to make the next color
575         * @param hue        -1f to 1f, the hue change that can be applied to the new float color (not clamped, wraps)
576         * @param saturation -1f to 1f, the saturation change that can be applied to the new float color
577         * @param value      -1f to 1f, the value/brightness change that can be applied to the new float color
578         * @param opacity    -1f to 1f, the opacity/alpha change that can be applied to the new float color
579         * @return a float encoding a variation of basis with the given changes
580         */
581        public static float toEditedFloat(float basis, float hue, float saturation, float value, float opacity) {
582                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(basis);
583                final float L = Math.min(Math.max(value + (decoded & 0xff) / 255f, 0f), 1f);
584                opacity = Math.min(Math.max(opacity + (decoded >>> 24 & 0xfe) * 0x1.020408p-8f, 0f), 1f);
585                if (L <= 0.001f)
586                        return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat((((int) (opacity * 255f) << 24) & 0xFE000000) | 0x808000);
587                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
588                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
589                final float l = cube(L + 0.3963377774f * A + 0.2158037573f * B);
590                final float m = cube(L - 0.1055613458f * A - 0.0638541728f * B);
591                final float s = cube(L - 0.0894841775f * A - 1.2914855480f * B);
592                final float r = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(+4.0767245293f * l - 3.3072168827f * m + 0.2307590544f * s, 0f), 1f));
593                final float g = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-1.2681437731f * l + 2.6093323231f * m - 0.3411344290f * s, 0f), 1f));
594                final float b = reverseGamma(Math.min(Math.max(-0.0041119885f * l - 0.7034763098f * m + 1.7068625689f * s, 0f), 1f));
595                float x, y, z, w;
596                if(g < b) {
597                        x = b;
598                        y = g;
599                        z = -1f;
600                        w = 2f / 3f;
601                }
602                else {
603                        x = g;
604                        y = b;
605                        z = 0f;
606                        w = -1f / 3f;
607                }
608                if(r < x) {
609                        z = w;
610                        w = r;
611                }
612                else {
613                        w = x;
614                        x = r;
615                }
616                final float d = x - Math.min(w, y);
617                final float light = x * (1f - 0.5f * d / (x + 1e-10f));
618                hue += Math.abs(z + (w - y) / (6f * d + 1e-10f)) + 1f;
619                saturation += (x - light) / (Math.min(light, 1f - light) + 1e-10f);
620                return fromRGBA(FloatColors.hsl2rgb(hue - (int)hue, Math.min(Math.max(saturation, 0f), 1f), light, opacity));
621        }

765        public static float dullen(final float start, final float change) {
766                final int s = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(start);
767                return oklab((s & 0xFF) / 255f,
768                                ((s >>> 8 & 0xFF) / 255f - 0.5f) * (1f - change) + 0.5f,
769                                ((s >>> 16 & 0xFF) / 255f - 0.5f) * (1f - change) + 0.5f,
770                                (s >>> 25) / 127f);
771        }

773        /**
774         * Pushes the chromatic components of {@code start} away from grayscale by change (saturating them). While change
775         * should be between 0f (return start as-is) and 1f (return maximally saturated), start should be a packed color, as
776         * from {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}. This usually changes only A and B, but higher values for
777         * {@code change} can force the color out of the gamut, which this corrects using
778         * {@link #limitToGamut(float, float, float, float)} (and that can change L somewhat). If the color stays in-gamut,
779         * then L won't change; alpha never changes.
780         * @see #dullen(float, float) the counterpart method that makes a float color less saturated
781         * @param start the starting color as a packed float
782         * @param change how much to change start to a saturated color, as a float between 0 and 1; higher means a more saturated result
783         * @return a packed float that represents a color between start and a saturated color
784         */
785        public static float enrich(final float start, final float change) {
786                final int s = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(start);
787                return limitToGamut((s & 0xFF) / 255f,
788                                ((s >>> 8 & 0xFF) / 255f - 0.5f) * (1f + change) + 0.5f,
789                                ((s >>> 16 & 0xFF) / 255f - 0.5f) * (1f + change) + 0.5f,
790                                (s >>> 25) / 127f);
791        }

794        /**
795         * Given a packed float Oklab color {@code mainColor} and another Oklab color that it should be made to contrast with,
796         * gets a packed float Oklab color with roughly inverted L but the same chromatic channels and opacity (A and B
797         * are likely to be clamped if the result gets close to white or black). This won't ever produce black or other very
798         * dark colors, and also has a gap in the range it produces for L values between 0.5 and 0.55. That allows
799         * most of the colors this method produces to contrast well as a foreground when displayed on a background of
800         * {@code contrastingColor}, or vice versa. This will leave the L unchanged if the chromatic channels of the
801         * contrastingColor and those of the mainColor are already very different. This has nothing to do with the contrast
802         * channel of the tweak in ColorfulBatch; where that part of the tweak can make too-similar lightness values further
803         * apart by just a little, this makes a modification on {@code mainColor} to maximize its lightness difference from
804         * {@code contrastingColor} without losing its other qualities.
805         * @param mainColor a packed float color, as produced by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)};
806         *                     this is the color that will be adjusted
807         * @param contrastingColor a packed float color, as produced by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)};
808         *                            the adjusted mainColor will contrast with this
809         * @return a different Oklab packed float color, based on mainColor but with potentially very different lightness
810         */
811        public static float inverseLightness(final float mainColor, final float contrastingColor)
812        {
813                final int bits = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(mainColor),
814                                contrastBits = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(contrastingColor),
815                                L = (bits & 0xff),
816                                A = (bits >>> 8 & 0xff),
817                                B = (bits >>> 16 & 0xff),
818                                cL = (contrastBits & 0xff),
819                                cA = (contrastBits >>> 8 & 0xff),
820                                cB = (contrastBits >>> 16 & 0xff);
821                if((A - cA) * (A - cA) + (B - cB) * (B - cB) >= 0x10000)
822                        return mainColor;
823                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat((bits & 0xFEFFFF00) | (int) (cL < 128 ? L * 0.45f + 140 : 127 - L * 0.45f));
824        }

826        /**
827         * Given a packed float Oklab color {@code mainColor} and another Oklab color that it should be made to contrast
828         * with, gets a packed float Oklab color with L that should be quite different from {@code contrastingColor}'s L,
829         * but the same chromatic channels and opacity (A and B are likely to be clamped if the result gets close to white
830         * or black). This allows most of the colors this method produces to contrast well as a foreground when displayed on
831         * a background of {@code contrastingColor}, or vice versa.
832         * <br>
833         * This is similar to {@link #inverseLightness(float, float)}, but is considerably simpler, and this method will
834         * change the lightness of mainColor when the two given colors have close lightness but distant chroma. Because it
835         * averages the original L of mainColor with the modified one, this tends to not produce harsh color changes.
836         * @param mainColor a packed Oklab float color; this is the color that will be adjusted
837         * @param contrastingColor a packed Oklab float color; the adjusted mainColor will contrast with the L of this
838         * @return a different packed Oklab float color, based on mainColor but typically with different lightness
839         */
840        public static float differentiateLightness(final float mainColor, final float contrastingColor)
841        {
842                final int main = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(mainColor), contrast = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(contrastingColor);
843                return limitToGamut(BitConversion.intBitsToFloat((main & 0xFEFFFF00) | (contrast + 128 & 0xFF) + (main & 0xFF) >>> 1));
844        }

846        /**
847         * Pretty simple; adds 0.5 to the given color's L and wraps it around if it would go above 1.0, then averages that
848         * with the original L. This means light colors become darker, and dark colors become lighter, with almost all
849         * results in the middle-range of possible lightness.
850         * @param mainColor a packed Oklab float color
851         * @return a different packed Oklab float color, with its L channel changed and limited to the correct gamut
852         */
853        public static float offsetLightness(final float mainColor) {
854                final int oklab = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(mainColor);
855                return limitToGamut(BitConversion.intBitsToFloat((oklab & 0xFEFFFF00) | (oklab + 128 & 0xFF) + (oklab & 0xFF) >>> 1));
856        }

858        /**
859         * Makes the additive Oklab color stored in {@code color} cause less of a change when used as a tint, as if it were
860         * mixed with neutral gray. When {@code fraction} is 1.0, this returns color unchanged; when fraction is 0.0, it
861         * returns {@link Palette#GRAY}, and when it is in-between 0.0 and 1.0 it returns something between the two. This is
862         * meant for things like area of effect abilities that make smaller color changes toward their periphery.
863         * @param color a color that should have its tinting effect potentially weakened
864         * @param fraction how much of {@code color} should be kept, from 0.0 to 1.0
865         * @return an Oklab float color between gray and {@code color}
866         */
867        public static float lessenChange(final float color, float fraction) {
868                final int e = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(color),
869                                sL = 0x80, sA = 0x80, sB = 0x80, sAlpha = 0xFE,
870                                eL = (e & 0xFF), eA = (e >>> 8) & 0xFF, eB = (e >>> 16) & 0xFF, eAlpha = e >>> 24 & 0xFE;
871                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(((int) (sL + fraction * (eL - sL)) & 0xFF)
872                                | (((int) (sA + fraction * (eA - sA)) & 0xFF) << 8)
873                                | (((int) (sB + fraction * (eB - sB)) & 0xFF) << 16)
874                                | (((int) (sAlpha + fraction * (eAlpha - sAlpha)) & 0xFE) << 24));
875        }

877        /**
878         * Makes a quasi-randomly-edited variant on the given {@code color}, allowing typically a small amount of
879         * {@code variance} (such as 0.05 to 0.25) between the given color and what this can return. The {@code seed} should
880         * be different each time this is called, and can be obtained from a random number generator to make the colors more
881         * random, or can be incremented on each call. If the seed is only incremented or decremented, then this shouldn't
882         * produce two similar colors in a row unless variance is very small. The variance affects the L, A, and B of the
883         * generated color, and each of those channels can go up or down by the given variance as long as the total distance
884         * isn't greater than the variance (this considers A and B extra-wide, going from -1 to 1, while L goes from 0 to 1,
885         * but only internally for measuring distance).
886         * @param color a packed float color, as produced by {@link #oklab(float, float, float, float)}
887         * @param seed a long seed that should be different on each call; should not be 0
888         * @param variance max amount of difference between the given color and the generated color; always less than 1
889         * @return a generated packed float color that should be at least somewhat different from {@code color}
890         */
891        public static float randomEdit(final float color, long seed, final float variance) {
892                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(color);
893                final float L = (decoded & 0xff) / 255f;
894                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
895                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
896                final float limit = variance * variance;
897                float dist, x, y, z;
898                for (int j = 0; j < 50; j++) {
899                        x = (((seed * 0xD1B54A32D192ED03L >>> 41) - 0x7FFFFFp-1f) * 0x1p-22f) * variance;
900                        y = (((seed * 0xABC98388FB8FAC03L >>> 41) - 0x7FFFFFp-1f) * 0x1p-22f) * variance;
901                        z = (((seed * 0x8CB92BA72F3D8DD7L >>> 41) - 0x7FFFFFp-1f) * 0x1p-22f) * variance;
902                        seed += 0x9E3779B97F4A7C15L;
903                        dist = x * x + y * y + z * z;
904                        if(dist <= limit && inGamut(x += L, y = (A + y) * 0.5f + 0.5f, z = (B + z) * 0.5f + 0.5f))
905                                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat((decoded & 0xFE000000) | ((int)(z * 255.5f) << 16 & 0xFF0000)
906                                        | ((int)(y * 255.5f) << 8 & 0xFF00) | (int)(x * 255.5f));
907                }
908                return color;
909        }

922        /**
923         * Given a 1D int index between 0 and 65535 (both inclusive), this treats the 1D index as two parts (lightness and
924         * hue angle, both from 0 to 255) and gets the distance from grayscale to the edge of the gamut at that lightness
925         * and hue. The index can be constructed from a lightness value {@code L} from 0 to 255, and a hue value {@code H}
926         * from 0 to 255 with: {@code (L << 8 | H)} or the simpler equivalent {@code (L * 256 + H)}. These assume L and H
927         * have been limited to the 0 to 255 range already. This does not bounds-check index. Because hue is not typically
928         * measured between 0 and 255, getting that value is a bit different; you can use
929         * {@link MathTools#atan2_(float, float)} (with an Oklab color's B for y, then its A for x) and multiply it by 256
930         * to get H.
931         * <br>
932         * The distance this returns is a byte between 0 and 82 (both inclusive), as the Euclidean distance from the center
933         * grayscale value at the lightness in the index, to the edge of the gamut at the same lightness, along the hue in
934         * the index. This is measured in a space from -1 to 1 for both A and B, with the 0 in the center meaning grayscale,
935         * and multiplied by 256 to get a meaningful byte value. To return to the A and B values Oklab uses here, you would
936         * need to use some trigonometry on the hue (if it's in the 0 to 1 range, you can call
937         * {@link MathTools#cos_(float)} on the hue to almost get A, and {@link MathTools#sin_(float)} to almost get B),
938         * then multiply each of those by the distance, divide each by 256.0, and add 0.5.
939         * <br>
940         * Only intended for the narrow cases where external code needs read-only access to the internal Oklab gamut data.
941         * The gamut data is quite large (the Oklab ColorTools file is 236 KB at the time of writing, while the IPT_HQ
942         * ColorTools file is just 56 KB, with the main difference being the sizable exact gamut), so it's better to have
943         * direct read access to it without being able to accidentally rewrite it.
944         * @param index must be between 0 and 65535; the upper 8 bits are lightness and the lower 8 are hue angle.
945         * @return a byte (always between 0 and 82, inclusive) representing the Euclidean distance between a grayscale value and the most saturated value possible, using the above measurements
946         */
947        public static byte getRawGamutValue(int index){
948                return GAMUT_DATA[index];
949        }

951        /**
952         * Returns true if the given packed float color, as Oklab, is valid to convert losslessly back to RGBA.
953         * @param packed a packed float color as Oklab
954         * @return true if the given packed float color can be converted back and forth to RGBA
955         */
956        public static boolean inGamut(final float packed)
957        {
958                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
959                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
960                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
961                final int idx = (decoded & 0xff) << 8 | (int)(256f * MathTools.atan2_(B, A));
962                return GAMUT_DATA[idx] * 0x1p-8f >= (float) Math.sqrt(A * A + B * B);
963        }

965        /**
966         * Returns true if the given Oklab values are valid to convert losslessly back to RGBA.
967         * @param L lightness channel, as a float from 0 to 1
968         * @param A green-to-red chromatic channel, as a float from 0 to 1
969         * @param B blue-to-yellow chromatic channel, as a float from 0 to 1
970         * @return true if the given Oklab channels can be converted back and forth to RGBA
971         */
972        public static boolean inGamut(float L, float A, float B)
973        {
974                A = (A - 0.5f);
975                B = (B - 0.5f);
976                final int idx = ((int)(L * 255.999f) << 8) | (int)(256f * MathTools.atan2_(B, A));
977                return GAMUT_DATA[idx] * 0x1p-8f >= (float) Math.sqrt(A * A + B * B);
978        }

980        /**
981         * Gets the color with the same L as the Oklab color stored in the given packed float, but the furthest A
982         * B from gray possible for that lightness while keeping the same hue as the given color. This is very
983         * similar to calling {@link #enrich(float, float)} with a very large {@code change} value.
984         * @param packed a packed float color in Oklab format; does not need to be in-gamut
985         * @return the color that is as far from grayscale as this can get while keeping the L and hue of packed
986         * @see #limitToGamut(float) You can use limitToGamut() if you only want max saturation for out-of-gamut colors.
987         */
988        public static float maximizeSaturation(final float packed) {
989                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
990                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
991                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
992                final float hue = MathTools.atan2_(B, A);
993                final int idx = (decoded & 0xff) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
994                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx] * 0x1p-8f;
995                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(
996                                (decoded & 0xFE0000FF) |
997                                                (int) (MathTools.cos_(hue) * dist * 127.999f + 127.999f) << 8 |
998                                                (int) (MathTools.sin_(hue) * dist * 127.999f + 127.999f) << 16);
999        }

1001        /**
1002         * Gets the color with the same L as the Oklab color stored in the given packed float, but the furthest A
1003         * B from gray possible for that lightness while keeping the same hue as the given color. This is very
1004         * similar to calling {@link #enrich(float, float)} with a very large {@code change} value.
1005         * @param L lightness component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1006         * @param A green-to-red chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1007         * @param B blue-to-yellow chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1008         * @param alpha alpha component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1009         * @return the color that is as far from grayscale as this can get while keeping the L and hue of packed
1010         * @see #limitToGamut(float, float, float, float) You can use limitToGamut() if you only want max saturation for out-of-gamut colors.
1011         */
1012        public static float maximizeSaturation(float L, float A, float B, float alpha) {
1013                L = Math.min(Math.max(L, 0f), 1f);
1014                A = Math.min(Math.max(A, 0f), 1f);
1015                B = Math.min(Math.max(B, 0f), 1f);
1016                alpha = Math.min(Math.max(alpha, 0f), 1f);
1017                final float A2 = (A - 0.5f);
1018                final float B2 = (B - 0.5f);
1019                final float hue = MathTools.atan2_(B2, A2);
1020                final int idx = (int) (L * 255.999f) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
1021                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx] * 0x1p-8f;
1022                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(
1023                                (int) (alpha * 127.999f) << 25 |
1024                                                (int) (MathTools.sin_(hue) * dist * 127.999f + 127.999f) << 16 |
1025                                                (int) (MathTools.cos_(hue) * dist * 127.999f + 127.999f) << 8 |
1026                                                (int) (L * 255.999f));
1027        }
1028        /**
1029         * Checks whether the given Oklab color is in-gamut; if it isn't in-gamut, brings the color just inside
1030         * the gamut at the same lightness, or if it is already in-gamut, returns the color as-is.
1031         * @param packed a packed float color in Oklab format; often this color is not in-gamut
1032         * @return the first color this finds that is in-gamut, as if it was moving toward a grayscale color with the same L
1033         * @see #inGamut(float) You can use inGamut() if you just want to check whether a color is in-gamut.
1034         */
1035        public static float limitToGamut(final float packed) {
1036                final int decoded = BitConversion.floatToRawIntBits(packed);
1037                final float A = ((decoded >>> 8 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
1038                final float B = ((decoded >>> 16 & 0xff) - 127.5f) / 127.5f;
1039                final float hue = MathTools.atan2_(B, A);
1040                final int idx = (decoded & 0xff) << 8 | (int) (256f * hue);
1041                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx] * 0x1p-8f;
1042                if (dist >= (float) Math.sqrt(A * A + B * B))
1043                        return packed;
1044                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(
1045                                (decoded & 0xFE0000FF) |
1046                                                (int) (MathTools.cos_(hue) * dist * 127.999f + 127.999f) << 8 |
1047                                                (int) (MathTools.sin_(hue) * dist * 127.999f + 127.999f) << 16);
1048        }

1052         * the gamut at the same lightness, or if it is already in-gamut, returns the color as-is. This always produces
1053         * an opaque color.
1054         * @param L lightness component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already

1056         * @param B blue-to-yellow chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already

1060        public static float limitToGamut(float L, float A, float B) {
1061                return limitToGamut(L, A, B, 1f);

1064        /**
1065         * Checks whether the given Oklab color is in-gamut; if it isn't in-gamut, brings the color just inside
1066         * the gamut at the same lightness, or if it is already in-gamut, returns the color as-is.
1067         * @param L lightness component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1068         * @param A green-to-red chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1069         * @param B blue-to-yellow chromatic component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1070         * @param alpha alpha component; will be clamped between 0 and 1 if it isn't already
1071         * @return the first color this finds that is in-gamut, as if it was moving toward a grayscale color with the same L
1072         * @see #inGamut(float, float, float)  You can use inGamut() if you just want to check whether a color is in-gamut.
1073         */
1074        public static float limitToGamut(float L, float A, float B, float alpha) {
1075                L = Math.min(Math.max(L, 0f), 1f);
1076                A = Math.min(Math.max(A, 0f), 1f);
1077                B = Math.min(Math.max(B, 0f), 1f);
1078                alpha = Math.min(Math.max(alpha, 0f), 1f);
1079                final float A2 = (A - 0.5f);
1080                final float B2 = (B - 0.5f);
1081                final float hue = MathTools.atan2_(B2, A2);
1082                final int idx = (int) (L * 255.999f) << 8 | (int)(256f * hue);
1083                final float dist = GAMUT_DATA[idx] * 0x1p-8f;
1084                if(dist >= (float) Math.sqrt(A2 * A2 + B2 * B2))
1085                        return oklab(L, A, B, alpha);
1086                return BitConversion.intBitsToFloat(
1087                                (int) (alpha * 127.999f) << 25 |
1088                                                (int) (MathTools.sin_(hue) * dist * 127.999f + 127.999f) << 16 |
1089                                                (int) (MathTools.cos_(hue) * dist * 127.999f + 127.999f) << 8 |
1090                                                (int) (L * 255.999f));
1091        }

1093        /**
1094         * Produces a random packed float color that is always in-gamut (and opaque) and should be uniformly distributed.
1095         * @param random a Random object (preferably a subclass of Random, like
1096         * {@link com.github.tommyettinger.ds.support.LaserRandom})
1097         * @return a packed float color that is always in-gamut
1098         */
1099        public static float randomColor(Random random) {
1100                float L = random.nextFloat();
1101                float A = random.nextFloat();
1102                float B = random.nextFloat();
1103                while (!inGamut(L, A, B)) {
1104                        L = random.nextFloat();
1105                        A = random.nextFloat();
1106                        B = random.nextFloat();
1107                }
1108                return oklab(L, A, B, 1f);
1109        }
